Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Replace", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976971517887455*^9, 3.976971547142874*^9}, {
  3.9772468851690273`*^9, 3.9772469101449623`*^9}, {3.977501455301296*^9, 
  3.9775014556323357`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"583eb70b-17dc-ea4e-b2fe-\
2f98318b4045"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Now, we are going to introduce a couple of different ways Mathematica \
processes functions. We\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll mainly be focusing on some \
nuances of the syntax for a few different commands and explaining how \
Mathematica interprets them. Unfortunately, you will most likely have to \
learn through experience when to use the techniques presented here. \n\nThe \
first command we want to introduce is the",
 StyleBox[" Replace",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " command, denoted using slash-dot (/.). The replace command can replace \
symbols or placeholders with actual values. This can be useful if you want to \
have the symbolic expression readily available but still want to get numbers \
for specific parameters.  \n\nIn order to use the ",
 StyleBox["Replace ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "command, we also need what is called a rule. Rules take the form, \
<parameter> ->  <value>. The -> (dash-greater-than) symbol should turn into \
an arrow in Mathematica\[CloseCurlyQuote]s input cell.  A simple example is \
like below"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976971517887455*^9, 3.9769715485208187`*^9}, {
   3.977246450772932*^9, 3.9772464720028763`*^9}, {3.977246506341463*^9, 
   3.9772465256877575`*^9}, {3.9772465826819305`*^9, 
   3.9772465923542633`*^9}, {3.9772467009793205`*^9, 
   3.9772467306122875`*^9}, {3.9772469127315025`*^9, 3.977246913995699*^9}, {
   3.977248711276884*^9, 3.977248712647888*^9}, {3.977499002884161*^9, 
